The paper proposes a framework for cross-modal subspace learning, which involves learning a common subspace for different modalities. This is a problem that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision (cs.CV), multimedia (cs.MM), information retrieval (cs.IR), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Given that the paper focuses on learning a discriminative subspace representation, it is most likely to belong to the machine learning sub-category (cs.LG). However, given that the proposed framework involves constructing a graph model and maximizing kernel correlation, it is also relevant to the computer vision (cs.CV) and multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. The use of label information suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. Finally, the problem of cross-modal subspace learning is a fundamental problem in artificial intelligence (cs.AI), which makes this sub-category a likely candidate as well.
